:"Balkwill","meanings":["English: apparently a variant of   Bakewell  , from the place-name Bakewell (Derbys), which appears as  <i>Baukwell</i>,  <i>Bawkwell</i>, and the like throughout the Middle Ages. The distribution suggests a south-western origin, with regional  <i>-will</i> for more general  <i>-well</i> ‘stream’, but no suitable place has been found; it may be irregular for one of the places called  <i>Blackwell</i> or  <i>Blakewell</i> in Devon, but on the face of it the first element is either Old English  <i>balca</i> ‘ridge, bank’ or  <i>bealluc</i> ‘testicle’. There is a Balkwell Farm in North Shields (Northumb) which can hardly be relevant."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Barkwell was born in 1505. She married John Blackshaw about 1529. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1595, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1505–1595":"1505–1595","1505–1565":"1505–1565","1526–1590":"1526–1590","about 1529":"umbes 1529","1 June 1526":"1. juuni 1526","1 Jun 1565":"1. juuni 1565","1565":"1565","1595":"1595","1 June 1590":"1. juuni 1590","1590":"1590","1505":"1505","1526":"1526","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Withington, Cheshir